          "body": "Verses 5-7 describe Israel's descent in two movements: social integration (living among, intermarrying with, 3:5-6a) followed by religious capitulation (serving their gods, 3:6b). The sequence is important — the narrator does not depict Israel making a sudden, dramatic defection to paganism. The failure is gradual and social, driven by proximity and marriage. Deuteronomy 7:3-4 had warned explicitly against intermarriage, naming its precise danger: 'they will turn your sons away from following Me to serve other gods.' Judges 3:6 is that warning fulfilled. The narrator's theological verdict comes in 3:7: Israel 'forgot the LORD their God.' Shakhach — forgetting — is the root diagnosis. Idolatry is not primarily an intellectual error but a devotional failure, a failure of memory and attention. The book of Deuteronomy uses 'remember' and 'forget' as the two poles of covenant faithfulness; the Shema's command to keep the words 'upon your heart' (Deuteronomy 6:6) is precisely the antidote to the forgetting that produces Baal-worship. Judges 3:7 names not just what Israel did but why: they forgot."
