          "body": "The central theological claim of Judges 3 is not about the deliverers but about the Deliverer behind them. In both full cycles, the Lord is the active agent at every stage: He left the nations (3:1), He tested Israel (3:4), His anger burned (3:8), He sold Israel into bondage (3:8), He raised up the deliverers (3:9, 15), His Spirit empowered Othniel (3:10), He gave the enemies into hand (3:10, 28). Israel's only contribution is to cry out (zaaq, 3:9, 15) — and even the timing of that cry, after the pain of servitude has become unbearable, is not presented as virtuous. The Reformed tradition has rightly recognized in the Judges pattern an illustration of common grace and prevenient mercy — God rescuing people who have given Him no reason to do so. The Arminian tradition equally recognizes the conditionality of the rescue upon Israel's cry — the pattern does not run automatically; it runs when the people turn. Both observations are textually accurate: the cry is necessary (it triggers the raise-up), but the raising-up is entirely God's initiative and God's provision. What the pattern does not promise — and what Judges' larger arc will painfully demonstrate — is that grace repeated without genuine repentance eventually gives way to judgment unreversed. The eighty years of rest (3:30) is the longest in the book, but the cycle starts again before the chapter ends."
