        "excerpt": "The sons of Israel did what was evil in the sight of the LORD, and forgot the LORD their God and served the Baals and the Asheroth.",
        "body": "Three verses describe what took generations to accomplish. Israel moved from **dwelling among** (3:5) to **intermarrying with** (3:6a) to **serving the gods of** (3:6b) the nations God had left as a test — and failed the test at every level. The sequence is deliberate and instructive: the failure is not dramatic apostasy but gradual accommodation. They lived among the Canaanites; they did not expel them as commanded (Joshua 23:12-13 had warned precisely this). Living became socializing; socializing became marriage; marriage became worship. Deuteronomy 7:3-4 had identified intermarriage as the critical vulnerability: 'they will turn your sons away from following Me to serve other gods.' Judges 3:6 is the fulfillment of that warning, detail for detail.\n\nThe narrator's theological verdict comes in the compressed summary of 3:7: 'forgot the LORD their God.' The Hebrew shakhach is not innocent forgetfulness — it is the willful, habitual inattention that Moses had warned against repeatedly in Deuteronomy (6:12; 8:11, 14, 19; 26:13). To forget Yahweh is to cease treating Him as the center of one's covenantal obligations. The Shema's demand that the words of Torah be 'upon your heart' and 'talked of when you sit in your house and when you walk by the way' (Deuteronomy 6:6-7) is the antidote to exactly this forgetting. Israel abandoned the practices that maintained memory — the household instruction, the feast-day rituals, the annual covenant renewals — and the result was predictable: they forgot, and then they served Baal.\n\nBaal and Asherah are not arbitrary substitutes; they are the Canaanite fertility deities whose worship promised agricultural abundance through ritual acts the Mosaic covenant explicitly prohibited. The appeal was economic and practical: the land required rain, and Baal was the storm-god who controlled it; the land required fertility, and Asherah was the goddess who ensured it. Israel was trading the covenant God for agricultural insurance. Calvin notes on this passage that idolatry is always, at its root, a practical calculation — we serve what we believe will provide what we need, and when we doubt that the covenant God will provide, we supplement Him with alternatives.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shakhach* (forgot, 3:7) is used forty-three times in Deuteronomy alone — it is the book's great warning verb. *Baalim* and *Asheroth* (plural forms) suggest not one local cult but a pervasive network of shrines; the apostasy was geographically widespread, not isolated."
