        "excerpt": "After him came Shamgar the son of Anath, who struck down six hundred Philistines with an oxgoad; and he also saved Israel.",
        "body": "Shamgar's single verse is one of the most studied single sentences in the book of Judges, precisely because of what it omits. It lacks every formulaic element that defined the Othniel and Ehud cycles: there is no sin-notice ('the sons of Israel did evil'), no oppression duration, no cry to the LORD, no Spirit-empowerment, no rest period. His name is non-Israelite in form, and his patronymic 'son of Anath' may connect him to the Canaanite war goddess Anat — raising the question of whether Shamgar is even an Israelite. He reappears only in the Song of Deborah (5:6), where his era is remembered not for rest but for the fear that kept travelers off the main roads.\n\nThe instrument matters: an oxgoad (malmad, 3:31) is a pointed stick, typically eight feet long, used to drive cattle. It is the farming implement of a man with no access to conventional weapons — a detail that connects to the broader Judges and Samuel context of Israelite military poverty (1 Samuel 13:19-22 describes Israel's inability to forge iron weapons, leaving them with agricultural tools for warfare). Six hundred Philistines with an oxgoad is either a massive exaggeration for rhetorical effect or a testimony to the extraordinary provision of God through the most rudimentary means. The number six hundred will appear again at Samson's jawbone slaughter (15:15) and in other military contexts — it may be a conventional round number for a significant military engagement rather than an exact count.\n\nThe theological function of Shamgar's compressed account is to signal instability. The four-beat cycle that ran cleanly in Othniel and dramatically in Ehud does not complete itself in Shamgar. Commentators including Peter Davids and Barry Webb (The Book of Judges, NICOT) have noted that Judges uses the incompleteness of individual accounts to signal the book's larger downward trajectory: the closer the book gets to its end, the more the pattern breaks down. Shamgar is the first crack. He saved Israel — the narrator affirms that — but the absence of rest, the non-Israelite name, and the missing theological framework suggest a deliverer operating at the margins of the covenant community, or a rescue that was less complete than the formula would require. What the book of Judges is moving toward is a situation in which no deliverer can complete the cycle — because the people's apostasy has become structural rather than episodic."
